President Joseph R. Biden, Jr. has declared a state of emergency in Connecticut due to the emergency conditions resulting from Tropical Storm Henri. This declaration authorizes the Department of Homeland Security, specifically the Federal Emergency Management Agency (FEMA), to coordinate disaster relief efforts and provide assistance to save lives, protect property and public health, and lessen the threat of a catastrophe. FEMA is authorized to identify, mobilize, and provide necessary equipment and resources to alleviate the impacts of the emergency. The emergency protective measures will be provided at 75 percent federal funding and will include mass care, evacuation, and shelter support. Robert V. Fogel has been named as the Federal Coordinating Officer for Federal recovery operations in the affected areas. For further information, the media can contact the FEMA News Desk.